initial_story:
The Eurovision Song Contest is just around the corner and this year, it's taking place in Malmo, Sweden.

You can find out all about the event right here.

The UK's entry for 2024 is Olly Alexander who'll be performing his song, Dizzy.

But how's he feeling ahead of the big night, where he'll perform in front of 200 million people!

De-Graft sat down with him to find out all about his preparation for the competition.

The Eurovision Song contest Grand Final will be shown on BBC One and iPlayer on Saturday 11 May.
stories:
Olly took a deep breath as he sat across from De-Graft, his nerves evident despite his calm exterior. "I'm feeling a mix of excitement and anxiety," he admitted. "The scale of the Eurovision audience is something I've never experienced before. But I'm focusing on the positive - the opportunity to share my music with so many people and represent the UK on the world stage."

As the interview continued, Olly spoke about his creative process behind "Dizzy," the song that would carry his Eurovision hopes. He also shared insights into his preparation for the contest, including vocal training and rehearsals.

"It's all about giving a strong performance on the night," Olly emphasized. "I want to do justice to the song and do my best for the UK."

The interview concluded with Olly expressing his gratitude for the support he's received from fans and well-wishers. "I couldn't be here without them," he said with a smile. "I'll be giving it my all on May 11th."

The Eurovision Song Contest Grand Final will be shown on BBC One and iPlayer on Saturday 11 May. Don't miss it!

Olly's voice filled the room as he continued to share his thoughts with the interviewer. "I've been working closely with my team to make sure every detail is perfect," he explained. "From the costumes to the choreography, we want to put on a memorable performance that will resonate with the Eurovision audience."

Despite the pressure, Olly remained confident and focused. "I believe in the power of my song and my ability to connect with people through music," he declared. "I'm excited to be a part of such a diverse and talented lineup of artists. It's an honor to represent the UK on the world stage."

As the interview drew to a close, Olly took a moment to reflect on the journey so far. "This experience has been a whirlwind, but I'm grateful for every moment of it," he said with a sincere smile. "I couldn't have gotten here without the support of my fans and team. I'm looking forward to sharing my music with the world on May 11th."

The Eurovision Song Contest Grand Final promises to be an unforgettable night of music and excitement. Don't miss Olly's performance on BBC One and iPlayer on Saturday 11 May.

Olly's enthusiasm was contagious as he looked towards the future. "I can't wait to step onto that stage and give it my all," he shared. "I know my fans will be there with me in spirit, cheering me on from around the world. And who knows, maybe we'll even bring home the win for the UK."

With a determined look in his eyes, Olly continued, "Every rehearsal, every interview, every moment leading up to the Grand Final is an opportunity to grow and improve. I'm taking it all in stride and learning from each experience."

As the interview came to an end, Olly expressed his gratitude once again. "I couldn't be here without the love and support of my fans, my team, and the UK. This is a dream come true, and I'm going to make the most of every moment."

Empowerment,

Olly's music continued to resonate with people around the world, inspiring them to embrace their unique identities and come together in the face of adversity. He collaborated with even more artists, pushing boundaries and breaking down barriers, proving that music knows no borders.

Despite the challenges and setbacks that came his way, Olly remained dedicated to using his platform for good, raising awareness for important social causes and encouraging fans to make a difference in their own communities. His music served as a beacon of hope, healing, and empowerment, helping people to find their voice and stand up for what they believed in.

As Olly looked out at the sea of faces before him, he felt a deep sense of pride and gratitude. He knew that his music had the power to make a difference in people's lives and bring them together, and he was committed to continuing to create music that would inspire and uplift, one song at a
